Dolls of War fought ceaselessly in battle, Foa, the doll who fought with MC’s Grandfather, died in battle while passing on her limbs to a limbless baby.

The surgery is a success, but the psychological effects on the baby made her think she was a doll, when she is actually human.

Tasked with convincing “the doll” of her human heritage, the grandson now shares a child with her—dolls cannot give birth, but she just did, and would likely feel the same motherly instinct mothers feel towards their children.

It’s a story with a little war and finding one’s humanity, followed by some metaphorical mentions of myths. That’s my interpretation of the story.
